AGI - "This is a watershed moment for Europe and Ukraine &nbsp;> as part of our European family. Europe faces a clear and present danger, and therefore Europe must be able to protect itself, defend itself, as we must put Ukraine in a position to protect itself and push for lasting and just peace. We want peace with strength, and that is why I present to the leaders the plan of rearmament of Europe". This was stated by the President of the European Commission, Ursula von der Leyen, jointly pressed with Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky and the President of the European Council, Antonio Costa, while in Brussels there is an extraordinary summit on defence.
"The rearmament plan provides up to 800 billion euros for defence investments. It offers Member States a tax area to invest in defence. It offers Member States the opportunity to invest in the Ukrainian defence industry or to provide military capabilities that go directly to Ukraine. So it is for the benefit of the rearmament of Europe, of the rearmament of the European Union, but also of the armament of Ukraine in its existential struggle for its sovereignty and territorial integrity. So today, Volodymyr, thank you for being here. It is a very important moment to show that we are alongside Ukraine for as long as necessary," he added.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
Meanwhile, Russia harshly criticized the French President, Emmanuel macron, who announced the intention of &nbsp; "opening a strategic discussion" on the protection of Europe with the French nuclear arsenal. &nbsp;>
<h2> The Kremlin, Macron wants the war to continue
The Kremlin denounced that Macron's speech demonstrates that France "wants war to continue". "This gives the feeling that France wants the war to continue," said spokesman Dmitri Peskov during a briefing with the press in which he defined the Elysian chief speech as "very conflict" against Russia.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h2>Lavrov, Macron nuclear rhetoric is a threat to Russia</h2>
"French President Emmanuel Macron's nuclear rhetoric is a threat to Russia," said Russian Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov, according to Ria Novosti. "Of course, this is a threat to Russia. If he considers us a threat, he summons a meeting of the leaders of the European countries and Britain, he says that it is necessary to use nuclear weapons, he prepares to use nuclear weapons against Russia, this is obviously a threat," said the head of Russian diplomacy, answering a question of journalists.
<h2>Lavrov, Macron as Napoleon and Hitler, but "less elegant"</h2>
Russian Foreign Minister Serghei Lavrov compared the statements of French President Emmanuel Macron to the words of Hitler and Napoleon. "Unlike his predecessors, Napoleon and Hitler, who also wanted to fight Russia, Macron is not acting very elegantly," he observed the head of the Russian Foreign Ministry in a press conference quoted by the Tass. Napoleon and Hitler, Lavrov recalled, "they said directly: We must conquer Russia, we must defeat Russia. And Macron, apparently, wants the same thing, but for some reason he claims that we must fight Russia because it creates a threat to France and Europe." The head of Russian diplomacy then defined "stupid" the statements according to which Russia is preparing a war against Europe and France. President Vladimir Putin, added Lavrov, "is repeatedly expressed, defining such delusional and senseless thoughts".&nbsp;
<h2>Tajani, it is impossible to guarantee security without the U.S.
"It seems absolutely impossible to think about securing the security of Ukraine and Europe without a solid transatlantic relationship, without NATO. It is fundamental, we have said it since the beginning, that without the United States we cannot do." Antonio Tajani, Vice-Premier and Minister of Foreign Affairs, said this when he arrived at the Ppe pre-vertice. "This also means that we must do our part, i.e. spend more on our safety. Security is not war, it also means the safety of our roads, our fellow citizens who live every day, perhaps taking risks. It means a lot, you don't have to simplify. Security is something much wider than war. No one wants war," he added.&nbsp;
