AGI – On Sunday, March 9, the 25th anniversary of the London Eye>, a structure destined to be a temporary sign of the millennium, which has now consolidated its place as an iconic landmark in London, shoulder to shoulder with the Big Ben, the Tower Bridge and St Paul's Cathedral.&nbsp;
Today, to celebrate its 25th anniversary, the London Eye presents a short film full of stars; 'Turning 25: London's Eye'.&nbsp;Through exclusive interviews with famous characters (Russell Tovey, Leigh-Anne Pinnock, David Harewood and Oleksandr Usyk>), personal stories of Londoners and an original piece of poetry spoken by the London Performative poet Emmanuel Speaks, the film retraces the history of the London Eye and its journey as a temporary monument The film is a love letter in London, which follows the evolution of London and London Eye in the last quarter of a century.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
<br Since 2000, the London Eye has welcomed more than 85 million visitors from all over the world, has become the heart of the annual New Year celebrations in London; He was the protagonist of the coronation of the royals, the Jubilee of London, the Olympic celebrations of 2012 and other historical events. The iconic structure has also consolidated its place in popular culture, appearing in hundreds of films and TV shows, including Mission Impossible, Harry Potter and the Order of Phoenix and Doctor Who. He also hosted thousands of celebrities, from the royal English family, with Prince and Princess of Wales, to celebrities in the world of entertainment such as Kate Moss and Kim Kardashian.
<br
Julia Barfield>, half of the entrepreneurial duo of architects - husband and wife - who designed and realized the structure, is the first of the testimonials. It shares the compelling journey of how the London Eye has passed from a concept created for a national competition (that no one won, since the judges felt that none of the ideas were valid enough), to become the iconic point of reference that is today.&nbsp;
<br> Julia Barfield, by Marks Barfield Architects who designed the London Eye, said: "The wheel was born as a reference point to celebrate the Millennium, but now has become a permanent feature of the London skyline.
<br> "It was David, my husband, to think about the wheel, and I placed it in the center of London. It is a symbol of time and a great way to get people up efficiently, and offer them the opportunity to see London from a new perspective and raise the mood.
<br> "It is incredibly moving to see so many people enjoy the structure: I came back to see her after so long. And it shows that if you have a dream, you just have to go ahead and realize it - don't wait for it to be asked. I just wish David was here to be part of it now."&nbsp;
<br> Robin Goodchild, Senior General Manager of the London Eye, said: "Celebrating a quarter of a century proudly sneaking into the skyline of London is not an enterprise recently, considering that initially the London Eye was designed to be a temporary structure. The fact that we are still here is a testimony of how London and the world have welcomed the London Eye as something more than the sum of its parts, turning it into a symbol of London. Like the Eye of London.”
<br> "We are really excited that all those who have been on the London Eye in the last 25 years can relive their incredible memories of the visit by watching the short film. And for those who have not yet had the opportunity to enter one of our 32 capsules, we hope that this inspires them to embark on a journey along the skyline of London and fall in love with the incredible city that we are proud to call home”.
&nbsp;
